Myocarditis

Myocardial dysfunction of inflammatory origin -> myocarditis.
Myocardial dysfunction of unknown origin -> Cardiomyopathy.

Etiology

  • Chaga's disease is one of the most common causes worldwide. Usually seen in south america.
  • In europe, most common causes are viruses.
  • Adenovirus, enterovirus, parvovirus B19 and HHV-6 are the commonest causes.

Presentation:

  • Develops in otherwise well young adults.
  • Patient presents with new onset heart failure / arrhythmia.
  • Course can be short and self limited or fulminant.
    Signs:
  • Prominent third heart sound S3.
  • Pericardial friction rub.

Diagnosis:

  • histologic biopsy is the gold standard but is not usually required as it won't change management.

    • histology will show lymphocytic infiltrate in viral causes.

  • Only time it is required is when giant cell myocarditis is suspected.

    • GCM is a severe form of myocarditis with poor prognosis. Multinucleated giant cells are seen on histology.

  • ECG - concave ST-elevations, AV block.

  • Echo will show wall motion abnormalities.

  • Cardiovascular magnetic resonance is done to confirm the diagnosis. -> Myocardial oedema and patchy gadolinium enhancement is present.

  • Troponin levels are commonly elevated

Management

  • Self limited in the majority.
  • Avoid athletic activity for 6 months.
  • If patient deteriorates, ECMO or Heart transplant
  • Immunosupprestants - only for certain causes.

    • Immunosuppressive therapy is suggested for specific autoreactive disorders such as GCM, sarcoidosis, noninfectious eosinophilic myocarditis, and autoreactive myocarditis

Insulin binds to the insulin receptor -> The beta subunits of the receptor have tyrosine kinase activity.

  • Older / black people - lower renin levels -> lower effectiveness of RAAS blockade.
  • Younger white people - higher renin -> RAAS blockade is more effective.

Postpartum hypertension, which affects approximately 2% of pregnancies -> hypertension occurring after delivery through 6 weeks postpartum , but also includes patients whose hypertension persists from antenatal period.
Source

Blood pressure normally peaks three to six days postpartum.

About 5.7% of cases of preeclampsia or eclampsia may develop in the post partum period (up to six weeks),

Gestational hypertension and preeclampsia (two common causes of persisting postpartum hypertension) usually resolve by 12 weeks.
Beyond 12 weeks, a secondary cause should be sought.

Studies show both beta blockers and calcium channel blockers can effectively control blood pressures postpartum

  • Treatment is recommended if BP > 140/80.

    • Uniquely, treatment can be down titrated once the targets are achieved.

  • Can use enalapril with monitoring of renal function and potassium.

  • Avoid diuretics and ARBs in post partum period.

  • Avoid methyldopa as it carries risk of depression.

  • Target a rate of fall of
    • ketones of 0.5 mmol/L/hr or
    • rise of HCO3 of 3mmol/L/hr.
  • Blood glucose fall of (at least ) 3mmol / L / hr (54 mg/dL / Hr)
  • If blood glucose falls below 14mmol/L (252 mg/Ld) add 10% dextrose 125 ml/hr.
    • Note "Add" not "replace"
    • But bicarb may be reduced due to hyperchloraemic acidosis caused by N/S administration.
    • Urinary ketones are not reliable as a indicator of resolution as they can persist after DKA resolution.

Typhoid

Salmonellae are motile gram-negative bacilli that infect or colonize a wide range of mammalian hosts.

Enteric fever

[!TIP] Fever + abdominal pain + GI symptoms

  • They cause diarrhoea by using a enterotoxin AND invading the mucosa.
    Symptoms: "stepwise" fever + chills + abdominal pain 5-21 days after exposure. (Not rapid like cholera )
    Rose spots are non tender, blanching papules. - occurs in 2nd week.
    By 4th week, gradual improvement.
  • Of little clinical value because it's positive even with previous infection. Also has low specificity.
  • Checks antibodies to O and H antigens of salmonella.

Treatment:

  • Resistance is common to chloramphenicol, amoxicillin, cotrimoxazole.
  • Fluoroquinolones [[Antibiotics#Ciprofloxacin|Cipfofloxacin]] -> ? resistant -> Ceftriaxone / cefotaxine -> ? resistant -> azithromycin / Meropenem;
  • but there is resistance to cipro and quinolones in pakistan. These are called extensively drug resistant typhoid.
    Prevention: two types of vaccinations are given : live attenuated (oral) and antigen based (IM)

Nontyphoidal salmonella

  • Most nontyphoidal Salmonella infections are caused by S. enterica subspecies enterica serotype Enteritidis, S. Typhimurium, S. Newport, S. Heidelberg, and S. Javiana
    • Infants, and those aged > 60 are at higher risk of severe disease.
  • creatinine is not reabsorbed
  • urea is reabsorbed by tubules via regulation

More than 99% of urea synthesis occurs in the liver. Its primary source is dietary protein. In the gut, the protein is converted into peptides and amino acids, more than 90% of which are absorbed and carried to the liver. In the hepatocyte, the amino acids are deaminated and transaminated. The resulting excess nitrogen feeds into the urea cycle to be incorporated into urea.
